\id SNG - Free Bible Version
\h Song of Songs
\toc2 Song of Songs
\toc1 Song of Songs
\mt1 Song of Solomon
\c 1
\p 
\v 1 \w Solomon|strong="H8010"\w*'s \w song|strong="H7892"\w* \w of|strong="H7892"\w* \w songs|strong="H7892"\w*.\f + \fr 1:1 \ft Each speaker is not explicitly identified in the Hebrew text as shown in this translation, but it is usually clear from the context and gender of the words used who is speaking. Additionally this book is poetry, and therefore translation needs to be more fluid than with prose.\f*
\sp Woman:
\p 
\v 2 \w Kiss|strong="H5401"\w* \w me|strong="H3588"\w*, \w kiss|strong="H5401"\w* \w me|strong="H3588"\w* \w with|strong="H6310"\w* \w your|strong="H3588"\w* \w mouth|strong="H6310"\w* again \w and|strong="H2896"\w* again,\f + \fr 1:2 \ft Literally, “Let him kiss me with the kisses of his mouth.” The repetition of the word “kiss” forms a superlative, just as “song of songs” really means “the best song.” In addition the poem begins in the third person but then immediately switches to the second person. Such changes are smoothed out for less confusing reading.\f* \w for|strong="H3588"\w* \w your|strong="H3588"\w* \w love|strong="H1730"\w* \w is|strong="H2896"\w* sweeter\f + \fr 1:2 \ft Literally, “better.”\f* \w than|strong="H2896"\w* \w wine|strong="H3196"\w*.
\v 3 \w I|strong="H5921"\w* love \w the|strong="H5921"\w* \w way|strong="H5921"\w* \w you|strong="H5921"\w* \w smell|strong="H7381"\w* \w from|strong="H5921"\w* \w the|strong="H5921"\w* perfumed \w oils|strong="H8081"\w* \w you|strong="H5921"\w* \w use|strong="H7381"\w*. \w You|strong="H5921"\w* \w have|strong="H8034"\w* quite \w a|strong="H3068"\w* \w reputation|strong="H8034"\w*\f + \fr 1:3 \ft Literally, “name.”\f*—\w it|strong="H5921"\w* spreads \w like|strong="H3651"\w* spilled perfumed \w oil|strong="H8081"\w*. \w It|strong="H5921"\w*'s not surprising \w that|strong="H3651"\w* \w all|strong="H5921"\w* \w the|strong="H5921"\w* \w young|strong="H2896"\w* women adore \w you|strong="H5921"\w*!
\v 4 \w Take|strong="H8055"\w* \w me|strong="H4900"\w* \w by|strong="H7323"\w* \w the|strong="H2142"\w* hand—\w let|strong="H1523"\w*'s \w run|strong="H7323"\w*! (\w The|strong="H2142"\w* \w king|strong="H4428"\w*\f + \fr 1:4 \ft In love poetry of the time “king” was also a term of endearment.\f* \w has|strong="H4428"\w* \w brought|strong="H7323"\w* \w me|strong="H4900"\w* \w to|strong="H4428"\w* \w his|strong="H2142"\w* \w bedroom|strong="H2315"\w*.) \w Let|strong="H1523"\w*'s \w be|strong="H4428"\w* \w happy|strong="H8055"\w* together \w and|strong="H4428"\w* find \w pleasure|strong="H8055"\w* \w in|strong="H4428"\w* \w your|strong="H2142"\w* \w love|strong="H1730"\w*.\f + \fr 1:4 \ft The verb moves to the first person plural, which could mean the change of speaker (some versions believe this line is spoke by the “friends” of the woman). However, it is taken here to be an inclusive form, indicating the woman and the man together.\f* \w Your|strong="H2142"\w* \w love|strong="H1730"\w* \w is|strong="H4428"\w* far better \w than|strong="H4428"\w* \w wine|strong="H3196"\w*! Women \w are|strong="H4428"\w* \w right|strong="H4339"\w* \w to|strong="H4428"\w* adore \w you|strong="H8055"\w* \w so|strong="H7323"\w*!\f + \fr 1:4 \ft Referring back to the young women of verse 3.\f*
\p 
\v 5 I'm \w black|strong="H7838"\w*, \w but|strong="H7838"\w* I'm beautiful, \w women|strong="H1323"\w* \w of|strong="H1323"\w* \w Jerusalem|strong="H3389"\w*,\f + \fr 1:5 \ft Her dark complexion was an issue for these women of Jerusalem, as it still is in some societies. Accordingly the woman tells them not to look down on her (verse 6).\f* \w like|strong="H1323"\w* \w the|strong="H8010"\w* tents \w of|strong="H1323"\w* \w Kedar|strong="H6938"\w*, \w like|strong="H1323"\w* \w the|strong="H8010"\w* \w curtains|strong="H3407"\w* \w of|strong="H1323"\w* \w Solomon|strong="H8010"\w*.
\v 6 Don't \w look|strong="H7200"\w* \w down|strong="H7760"\w* \w on|strong="H7200"\w* \w me|strong="H7200"\w* because \w I|strong="H7760"\w*'m \w black|strong="H7840"\w*, because \w the|strong="H7200"\w* \w sun|strong="H8121"\w* \w has|strong="H8121"\w* \w burned|strong="H2787"\w* \w me|strong="H7200"\w*. \w My|strong="H7760"\w* \w brothers|strong="H1121"\w* \w were|strong="H1121"\w* \w angry|strong="H5201"\w* \w with|strong="H8121"\w* \w me|strong="H7200"\w* \w and|strong="H1121"\w* \w made|strong="H7760"\w* \w me|strong="H7200"\w* \w look|strong="H7200"\w* \w after|strong="H7200"\w* \w the|strong="H7200"\w* \w vineyards|strong="H3754"\w*, \w so|strong="H3808"\w* \w I|strong="H7760"\w* couldn't \w look|strong="H7200"\w* \w after|strong="H7200"\w* \w my|strong="H7760"\w* own \w vineyard|strong="H3754"\w*.\f + \fr 1:6 \ft In other words, the woman could not look after herself. Note also that in literature of the time, “vineyard” was often used as a fertility metaphor.\f*
\v 7 \w My|strong="H5921"\w* love, please \w tell|strong="H5046"\w* \w me|strong="H5315"\w* \w where|strong="H4100"\w* \w you|strong="H5921"\w*'re taking \w your|strong="H5921"\w* \w flock|strong="H5739"\w*. \w Where|strong="H4100"\w* \w will|strong="H1961"\w* \w you|strong="H5921"\w* \w rest|strong="H7257"\w* \w them|strong="H5921"\w* \w at|strong="H5921"\w* \w noon|strong="H6672"\w*? \w For|strong="H5921"\w* \w why|strong="H4100"\w* \w should|strong="H4100"\w* \w I|strong="H5921"\w* \w have|strong="H1961"\w* \w to|strong="H1961"\w* \w wear|strong="H1961"\w* \w a|strong="H3068"\w* veil \w while|strong="H1961"\w* \w looking|strong="H1961"\w* \w for|strong="H5921"\w* \w you|strong="H5921"\w*\f + \fr 1:7 \ft “Looking for you”: implied.\f* \w among|strong="H5921"\w* \w the|strong="H5921"\w* \w flocks|strong="H5739"\w* \w of|strong="H5921"\w* \w your|strong="H5921"\w* \w companions|strong="H2270"\w*?\f + \fr 1:7 \ft The idea seems to be that the woman may have to hide herself during her search if she does not know where her love will be. Some have suggested that wearing a veil in such circumstances may have been like prostitutes who wished to keep their identity secret. Others suggest that the woman thinks other men may be attracted to her and she wishes to avoid that. Yet others suggest emending the text from “wear a veil” to “wander.”\f*
\sp Man
\p 
\v 8 If \w you|strong="H5921"\w* really don't \w know|strong="H3045"\w*, \w you|strong="H5921"\w* \w who|strong="H7462"\w* \w are|strong="H3045"\w* \w more|strong="H3808"\w* \w beautiful|strong="H3303"\w* \w than|strong="H3808"\w* \w any|strong="H3808"\w* other woman, \w then|strong="H3318"\w* follow \w the|strong="H5921"\w* tracks \w of|strong="H5921"\w* \w my|strong="H5921"\w* \w flock|strong="H6629"\w*, \w and|strong="H6629"\w* \w let|strong="H3808"\w* \w your|strong="H5921"\w* \w goats|strong="H1429"\w* \w graze|strong="H7462"\w* \w near|strong="H5921"\w* \w the|strong="H5921"\w* \w shepherd|strong="H7462"\w*'s \w tents|strong="H4908"\w*.
\v 9 My \w darling|strong="H7474"\w*, \w to|strong="H1819"\w* \w me|strong="H1819"\w* you're \w like|strong="H1819"\w* \w a|strong="H3068"\w* \w mare|strong="H5484"\w* among \w Pharaoh|strong="H6547"\w*'s \w horses|strong="H7393"\w*\f + \fr 1:9 \ft To be compared to a horse is not a modern-day complement, but this serves as a reminder that this is a very different culture than today. In addition chariots were pulled by stallions, so there may be some additional meaning here.\f* \w that|strong="H6547"\w* pull \w his|strong="H1819"\w* \w chariots|strong="H7393"\w*,
\v 10 \w Your|strong="H4998"\w* \w beautiful|strong="H4998"\w* \w cheeks|strong="H3895"\w* adorned \w with|strong="H6677"\w* \w ornaments|strong="H8447"\w*,\f + \fr 1:10 \ft It seems the ornaments the woman is wearing reminds the man of the decorations worn by the chariot horses.\f* \w your|strong="H4998"\w* \w neck|strong="H6677"\w* \w with|strong="H6677"\w* \w strings|strong="H2737"\w* \w of|strong="H6677"\w* jewels.
\v 11 Let's \w make|strong="H6213"\w* \w you|strong="H6213"\w* some \w gold|strong="H2091"\w* \w ornaments|strong="H8447"\w* \w inlaid|strong="H6213"\w* \w with|strong="H5973"\w* \w silver|strong="H3701"\w*.
\sp Woman:
\p 
\v 12 \w As|strong="H5704"\w* \w the|strong="H5414"\w* \w king|strong="H4428"\w* \w lay|strong="H5414"\w* \w on|strong="H5414"\w* \w his|strong="H5414"\w* couch, \w my|strong="H5414"\w* \w nard|strong="H5373"\w* \w perfume|strong="H5373"\w* \w gave|strong="H5414"\w* \w off|strong="H4428"\w* \w its|strong="H5414"\w* \w fragrance|strong="H7381"\w*.
\v 13 My \w love|strong="H1730"\w* \w is|strong="H1730"\w* \w like|strong="H7699"\w* \w a|strong="H3068"\w* \w pouch|strong="H6872"\w* \w of|strong="H6872"\w* \w myrrh|strong="H4753"\w*,\f + \fr 1:13 \ft A perfume placed in a small bag and worn on a string around the neck under clothes.\f* lying \w all|strong="H3885"\w* \w night|strong="H3885"\w* between my \w breasts|strong="H7699"\w*.
\v 14 My \w love|strong="H1730"\w* \w is|strong="H1730"\w* like \w a|strong="H3068"\w* bunch \w of|strong="H3754"\w* fragrant \w henna|strong="H3724"\w* flowers in the \w vineyards|strong="H3754"\w* \w of|strong="H3754"\w* \w Engedi|strong="H5872"\w*.\f + \fr 1:14 \ft Engedi means “spring of the young goat” and in the context may have a double meaning, together with the “vineyard” symbolism already mentioned.\f*
\sp Man:
\p 
\v 15 \w Look|strong="H2005"\w* \w at|strong="H5869"\w* how very \w beautiful|strong="H3303"\w* \w you|strong="H5869"\w* \w are|strong="H5869"\w*, my \w darling|strong="H7474"\w*, how \w beautiful|strong="H3303"\w*! \w Your|strong="H5869"\w* \w eyes|strong="H5869"\w* \w are|strong="H5869"\w* \w as|strong="H3303"\w* gentle \w as|strong="H3303"\w* \w doves|strong="H3123"\w*.
\sp Woman:
\p 
\v 16 \w And|strong="H3303"\w* you, my \w love|strong="H1730"\w*, are so \w handsome|strong="H3303"\w*—how charming you are! \w The|strong="H2005"\w* \w green|strong="H7488"\w* grass \w is|strong="H1730"\w* our \w bed|strong="H6210"\w*,
\v 17 \w with|strong="H1004"\w* cedar trees \w as|strong="H1004"\w* \w beams|strong="H6982"\w* \w for|strong="H1004"\w* our “\w house|strong="H1004"\w*,” \w and|strong="H1004"\w* pine trees \w for|strong="H1004"\w* \w the|strong="H1004"\w* \w rafters|strong="H7351"\w*.
\b
\c 2
\sp Woman:
\p 
\v 1 I'm just \w a|strong="H3068"\w* flower from the plain \w of|strong="H6010"\w* \w Sharon|strong="H8289"\w*, \w a|strong="H3068"\w* \w lily|strong="H7799"\w* found \w in|strong="H6010"\w* the \w valleys|strong="H6010"\w*.
\sp Man:
\p 
\v 2 Just \w as|strong="H3651"\w* \w a|strong="H3068"\w* \w lily|strong="H7799"\w* stands out \w among|strong="H7799"\w* \w the|strong="H3651"\w* \w brambles|strong="H2336"\w*, \w so|strong="H3651"\w* \w you|strong="H3651"\w*, \w my|strong="H3651"\w* \w darling|strong="H7474"\w*, stand out \w among|strong="H7799"\w* other \w women|strong="H1323"\w*.
\sp Woman:
\p 
\v 3 \w My|strong="H3651"\w* \w love|strong="H1730"\w* \w is|strong="H3651"\w* \w like|strong="H3651"\w* \w an|strong="H3427"\w* \w apple|strong="H8598"\w* \w tree|strong="H6086"\w*\f + \fr 2:3 \ft The apple is not usually grown in Israel so perhaps another fruit is meant. The main point is the contrast between a fruit tree and the ordinary trees of the forest that do not produce an edible fruit.\f* \w among|strong="H3427"\w* \w the|strong="H3651"\w* \w forest|strong="H3293"\w* \w trees|strong="H6086"\w*, compared \w to|strong="H1121"\w* other \w young|strong="H1121"\w* \w men|strong="H1121"\w*. \w I|strong="H3651"\w* \w love|strong="H1730"\w* \w to|strong="H1121"\w* \w sit|strong="H3427"\w* \w down|strong="H3427"\w* \w in|strong="H3427"\w* \w his|strong="H3427"\w* \w shade|strong="H6738"\w* \w and|strong="H1121"\w* \w his|strong="H3427"\w* \w fruit|strong="H6529"\w* tastes \w sweet|strong="H4966"\w* \w to|strong="H1121"\w* \w me|strong="H1121"\w*.
\v 4 \w He|strong="H1004"\w* took \w me|strong="H5921"\w* \w to|strong="H5921"\w* drink \w of|strong="H1004"\w* \w his|strong="H5921"\w* \w wine|strong="H3196"\w*,\f + \fr 2:4 \ft Literally, “He took me to the house of wine.”\f* wanting \w to|strong="H5921"\w* show \w his|strong="H5921"\w* love \w for|strong="H5921"\w* \w me|strong="H5921"\w*.\f + \fr 2:4 \ft The word often translated “banner” is more probably “intention” or “wish to.”\f*
\v 5 Feed \w me|strong="H3588"\w* raisins \w to|strong="H3588"\w* give \w me|strong="H3588"\w* energy, give \w me|strong="H3588"\w* \w apples|strong="H8598"\w* \w to|strong="H3588"\w* revive \w me|strong="H3588"\w*, \w for|strong="H3588"\w* love \w has|strong="H3588"\w* \w made|strong="H2470"\w* \w me|strong="H3588"\w* \w weak|strong="H2470"\w*!\f + \fr 2:5 \ft Or “I'm totally lovesick!”\f*
\v 6 \w He|strong="H8478"\w* supports \w my|strong="H8478"\w* \w head|strong="H7218"\w* \w with|strong="H7218"\w* \w his|strong="H8478"\w* \w left|strong="H8040"\w* \w hand|strong="H3225"\w*, \w and|strong="H7218"\w* holds \w me|strong="H8478"\w* close \w with|strong="H7218"\w* \w his|strong="H8478"\w* \w right|strong="H3225"\w*.
\v 7 \w Women|strong="H1323"\w* \w of|strong="H1323"\w* \w Jerusalem|strong="H3389"\w*, \w swear|strong="H7650"\w* \w to|strong="H5704"\w* \w me|strong="H3389"\w* \w by|strong="H7650"\w* \w the|strong="H5704"\w* \w gazelles|strong="H6643"\w* \w or|strong="H5704"\w* \w the|strong="H5704"\w* \w wild|strong="H7704"\w* deer \w that|strong="H5704"\w* \w you|strong="H5704"\w* won't disturb\f + \fr 2:7 \ft “Rouse” or “awaken” in the sense of “interrupt.” Since it's clear that love is already “awakened” in this situation, it seems that the woman is asking for privacy.\f* our \w love|strong="H5782"\w* \w until|strong="H5704"\w* \w the|strong="H5704"\w* right \w time|strong="H5704"\w*.
\p 
\v 8 \w Listen|strong="H6963"\w*! \w I|strong="H2009"\w* \w hear|strong="H6963"\w* \w the|strong="H5921"\w* \w voice|strong="H6963"\w* \w of|strong="H2022"\w* \w my|strong="H5921"\w* \w love|strong="H1730"\w*! \w Look|strong="H2009"\w*! \w Here|strong="H2009"\w* \w he|strong="H5921"\w* comes, \w leaping|strong="H1801"\w* \w on|strong="H5921"\w* \w the|strong="H5921"\w* \w mountains|strong="H2022"\w*, \w skipping|strong="H7092"\w* \w over|strong="H5921"\w* \w the|strong="H5921"\w* \w hills|strong="H1389"\w*—
\v 9 \w my|strong="H4480"\w* \w love|strong="H1730"\w* \w is|strong="H2088"\w* \w like|strong="H1819"\w* \w a|strong="H3068"\w* \w gazelle|strong="H6643"\w* \w or|strong="H4480"\w* \w a|strong="H3068"\w* \w young|strong="H6082"\w* deer! \w Look|strong="H2009"\w*, \w he|strong="H4480"\w*'s \w there|strong="H2009"\w*, \w standing|strong="H5975"\w* \w behind|strong="H4480"\w* \w our|strong="H4480"\w* \w wall|strong="H3796"\w*, \w looking|strong="H7688"\w* \w through|strong="H4480"\w* \w the|strong="H4480"\w* \w window|strong="H2474"\w*, \w peering|strong="H6692"\w* \w through|strong="H4480"\w* \w the|strong="H4480"\w* screen.
\v 10 \w My|strong="H6965"\w* \w love|strong="H1730"\w* calls \w out|strong="H3212"\w* \w to|strong="H3212"\w* \w me|strong="H6030"\w*, “\w Get|strong="H6965"\w* \w up|strong="H6965"\w*, \w my|strong="H6965"\w* \w darling|strong="H7474"\w*, \w my|strong="H6965"\w* \w beautiful|strong="H3303"\w* girl, \w and|strong="H6965"\w* \w come|strong="H3212"\w* \w away|strong="H3212"\w* \w with|strong="H3212"\w* \w me|strong="H6030"\w*! Just look!
\v 11 \w Winter|strong="H5638"\w* \w has|strong="H3588"\w* finished; \w the|strong="H3588"\w* \w rains|strong="H1653"\w* are \w over|strong="H5674"\w* \w and|strong="H1980"\w* \w gone|strong="H1980"\w*.
\v 12 \w Flowers|strong="H5339"\w* are blooming everywhere; \w the|strong="H8085"\w* \w time|strong="H6256"\w* \w when|strong="H7200"\w* \w birds|strong="H6963"\w* sing \w has|strong="H6256"\w* \w come|strong="H5060"\w*; \w the|strong="H8085"\w* \w call|strong="H8085"\w* \w of|strong="H6963"\w* \w the|strong="H8085"\w* \w turtledove|strong="H8449"\w* \w is|strong="H6963"\w* \w heard|strong="H8085"\w* \w in|strong="H8085"\w* \w the|strong="H8085"\w* countryside.\f + \fr 2:12 \ft The turtledove is a summer visitor to Israel. Its soft call “trrr-trrr” gives it its name, and is a sign that spring has come, like the arrival of the cuckoo in northern Europe.\f*
\v 13 \w Fig|strong="H8384"\w* \w trees|strong="H8384"\w* start producing ripe fruit, while \w grape|strong="H5563"\w* \w vines|strong="H1612"\w* \w blossom|strong="H5563"\w*, \w giving|strong="H5414"\w* \w off|strong="H5414"\w* \w their|strong="H5414"\w* \w fragrance|strong="H7381"\w*. \w Get|strong="H6965"\w* \w up|strong="H6965"\w*, \w my|strong="H5414"\w* \w darling|strong="H7474"\w*, \w my|strong="H5414"\w* \w beautiful|strong="H3303"\w* girl, \w and|strong="H6965"\w* \w come|strong="H3212"\w* \w away|strong="H3212"\w* \w with|strong="H3212"\w* \w me|strong="H5414"\w*!”
\sp Man:
\p 
\v 14 \w My|strong="H8085"\w* \w dove|strong="H3123"\w* \w is|strong="H6963"\w* \w out|strong="H7200"\w* \w of|strong="H6963"\w* \w sight|strong="H4758"\w* \w in|strong="H8085"\w* \w the|strong="H8085"\w* crevices \w of|strong="H6963"\w* \w the|strong="H8085"\w* \w rock|strong="H5553"\w*, \w in|strong="H8085"\w* \w the|strong="H8085"\w* \w hiding|strong="H5643"\w* \w places|strong="H4095"\w* \w of|strong="H6963"\w* \w the|strong="H8085"\w* \w cliff|strong="H5553"\w*. \w Please|strong="H8085"\w* let \w me|strong="H7200"\w* \w see|strong="H7200"\w* \w you|strong="H3588"\w*! Let \w me|strong="H7200"\w* \w hear|strong="H8085"\w* \w you|strong="H3588"\w*! \w For|strong="H3588"\w* \w you|strong="H3588"\w* speak \w so|strong="H3588"\w* sweetly, \w and|strong="H6963"\w* \w you|strong="H3588"\w* \w look|strong="H7200"\w* \w so|strong="H3588"\w* \w beautiful|strong="H4758"\w*!
\sp Woman:
\p 
\v 15 Catch \w the|strong="H2254"\w* \w foxes|strong="H7776"\w*\f + \fr 2:15 \ft Or “jackals.”\f* \w for|strong="H3754"\w* us, \w all|strong="H6996"\w* \w the|strong="H2254"\w* \w little|strong="H6996"\w* \w foxes|strong="H7776"\w* that come \w and|strong="H3754"\w* \w destroy|strong="H2254"\w* \w the|strong="H2254"\w* \w vineyards|strong="H3754"\w*, our \w vineyards|strong="H3754"\w* that are in bloom!\f + \fr 2:15 \ft The meaning of this verse, and the speaker, are both uncertain.\f*
\v 16 \w My|strong="H7462"\w* \w love|strong="H1730"\w* \w is|strong="H1730"\w* mine, \w and|strong="H7462"\w* I am \w his|strong="H7462"\w*! He \w feeds|strong="H7462"\w*\f + \fr 2:16 \ft Or “finds pleasure.”\f* \w among|strong="H7799"\w* \w the|strong="H7462"\w* \w lilies|strong="H7799"\w*,
\v 17 \w until|strong="H5704"\w* \w the|strong="H5921"\w* morning breezes \w blow|strong="H6315"\w* \w and|strong="H3117"\w* \w the|strong="H5921"\w* \w shadows|strong="H6752"\w* disappear. \w Come|strong="H5437"\w* \w back|strong="H5437"\w* \w to|strong="H5704"\w* \w me|strong="H5921"\w*, \w my|strong="H5921"\w* \w love|strong="H1730"\w*, \w and|strong="H3117"\w* \w be|strong="H3117"\w* \w like|strong="H1819"\w* \w a|strong="H3068"\w* \w gazelle|strong="H6643"\w* \w or|strong="H5704"\w* \w a|strong="H3068"\w* \w young|strong="H6082"\w* deer \w on|strong="H5921"\w* \w the|strong="H5921"\w* split \w mountains|strong="H2022"\w*.\f + \fr 2:17 \ft Literally, “the mountains of Bether.” However, there is no such place name known. Bether means split or cleft, indicating two mountains with a ravine dividing them.\f*
\b
\c 3
\sp Woman:
\p 
\v 1 \w One|strong="H3808"\w* \w night|strong="H3915"\w* \w when|strong="H5921"\w* \w I|strong="H5921"\w* \w was|strong="H5315"\w* \w lying|strong="H4904"\w* \w in|strong="H5921"\w* \w bed|strong="H4904"\w*, \w I|strong="H5921"\w* longed \w for|strong="H5921"\w* \w the|strong="H5921"\w* \w one|strong="H3808"\w* \w I|strong="H5921"\w* love. \w I|strong="H5921"\w* longed \w for|strong="H5921"\w* \w him|strong="H5921"\w*, \w but|strong="H3808"\w* \w he|strong="H3808"\w* \w was|strong="H5315"\w* \w nowhere|strong="H3808"\w* \w to|strong="H5921"\w* \w be|strong="H3808"\w* \w found|strong="H4672"\w*.
\v 2 \w So|strong="H3808"\w* \w I|strong="H5315"\w* said \w to|strong="H1245"\w* \w myself|strong="H5315"\w*,\f + \fr 3:2 \ft “So I told myself”: implied.\f* “\w I|strong="H5315"\w* \w will|strong="H5315"\w* \w get|strong="H6965"\w* \w up|strong="H6965"\w* \w now|strong="H4994"\w* \w and|strong="H6965"\w* \w go|strong="H5437"\w* \w through|strong="H4994"\w* \w the|strong="H6965"\w* \w city|strong="H5892"\w*, \w looking|strong="H1245"\w* \w in|strong="H5315"\w* \w its|strong="H6965"\w* \w streets|strong="H7339"\w* \w and|strong="H6965"\w* \w squares|strong="H7339"\w* \w for|strong="H5892"\w* \w the|strong="H6965"\w* \w one|strong="H3808"\w* \w I|strong="H5315"\w* love.” \w I|strong="H5315"\w* \w looked|strong="H1245"\w* \w for|strong="H5892"\w* \w him|strong="H4672"\w* \w but|strong="H3808"\w* \w I|strong="H5315"\w* didn't \w find|strong="H4672"\w* \w him|strong="H4672"\w*.
\v 3 \w The|strong="H7200"\w* \w watchmen|strong="H8104"\w* \w found|strong="H4672"\w* \w me|strong="H5315"\w* \w as|strong="H5315"\w* \w they|strong="H5315"\w* \w went|strong="H5892"\w* \w through|strong="H5892"\w* \w the|strong="H7200"\w* \w city|strong="H5892"\w*. “\w Have|strong="H4672"\w* \w you|strong="H7200"\w* \w seen|strong="H7200"\w* \w the|strong="H7200"\w* \w one|strong="H7200"\w* \w I|strong="H5315"\w* love?” \w I|strong="H5315"\w* asked \w them|strong="H7200"\w*.
\v 4 \w Only|strong="H5704"\w* \w a|strong="H3068"\w* \w little|strong="H4592"\w* farther \w on|strong="H5674"\w* \w after|strong="H1992"\w* \w I|strong="H5704"\w*'d \w passed|strong="H5674"\w* \w them|strong="H1992"\w* \w I|strong="H5704"\w* \w found|strong="H4672"\w* \w my|strong="H5674"\w* love! \w I|strong="H5704"\w* held \w him|strong="H4672"\w* \w close|strong="H4592"\w* \w and|strong="H1004"\w* \w would|strong="H5315"\w* \w not|strong="H3808"\w* \w let|strong="H7503"\w* \w him|strong="H4672"\w* \w go|strong="H5674"\w* \w until|strong="H5704"\w* \w I|strong="H5704"\w*'d \w brought|strong="H5674"\w* \w him|strong="H4672"\w* \w to|strong="H5704"\w* \w my|strong="H5674"\w* mother's \w house|strong="H1004"\w*, \w to|strong="H5704"\w* \w the|strong="H5704"\w* \w room|strong="H2315"\w* \w of|strong="H1004"\w* \w the|strong="H5704"\w* \w one|strong="H3808"\w* \w who|strong="H5315"\w* \w conceived|strong="H2029"\w* \w me|strong="H5315"\w*.\f + \fr 3:4 \ft “To the room of the one who conceived me”: or, “into the room of my conceiving,” which may be a euphemism for wishing to have a child.\f*
\v 5 \w Women|strong="H1323"\w* \w of|strong="H1323"\w* \w Jerusalem|strong="H3389"\w*, \w swear|strong="H7650"\w* \w to|strong="H5704"\w* \w me|strong="H3389"\w* \w by|strong="H7650"\w* \w the|strong="H5704"\w* \w gazelles|strong="H6643"\w* \w or|strong="H5704"\w* \w the|strong="H5704"\w* \w wild|strong="H7704"\w* deer \w that|strong="H5704"\w* \w you|strong="H5704"\w* won't disturb our \w love|strong="H5782"\w* \w until|strong="H5704"\w* \w the|strong="H5704"\w* right \w time|strong="H5704"\w*.
\sp Women of Jerusalem:
\p 
\v 6 \w Who|strong="H4310"\w* \w is|strong="H4310"\w* \w this|strong="H2063"\w* \w coming|strong="H5927"\w* \w in|strong="H5927"\w* \w from|strong="H4480"\w* \w the|strong="H3605"\w* \w wilderness|strong="H4057"\w* \w like|strong="H4057"\w* \w a|strong="H3068"\w* plume \w of|strong="H4057"\w* \w smoke|strong="H6227"\w*,\f + \fr 3:6 \ft The dust thrown up by travelers in a dry wilderness would be the first sign of their approach. However, the emphasis of this verse is certainly on the accompanying scent.\f* \w like|strong="H4057"\w* \w a|strong="H3068"\w* \w burning|strong="H6999"\w* \w sacrifice|strong="H6999"\w* scented \w with|strong="H5927"\w* \w myrrh|strong="H4753"\w* \w and|strong="H5927"\w* \w frankincense|strong="H3828"\w*, \w with|strong="H5927"\w* \w all|strong="H3605"\w* \w kinds|strong="H3605"\w* \w of|strong="H4057"\w* \w imported|strong="H5927"\w* \w perfumed|strong="H6999"\w* powders?\f + \fr 3:6 \ft Some see this speech of the women of Jerusalem as continuing through the next verses.\f*
\sp Woman:
\p 
\v 7 \w Look|strong="H2009"\w*, \w it|strong="H5439"\w*'s \w Solomon|strong="H8010"\w*'s sedan chair,\f + \fr 3:7 \ft Literally, “bed” or “couch.” A sedan chair was a portable chair used by royalty, carried on poles. It certainly was not a wheeled carriage, as some translations suggest.\f* accompanied \w by|strong="H3478"\w* \w sixty|strong="H8346"\w* \w of|strong="H1368"\w* \w Israel|strong="H3478"\w*'s best \w warriors|strong="H1368"\w*.
\v 8 \w All|strong="H3605"\w* \w of|strong="H5921"\w* \w them|strong="H5921"\w* \w are|strong="H4421"\w* \w expert|strong="H3925"\w* swordsmen \w who|strong="H3605"\w* \w have|strong="H3605"\w* \w battle|strong="H4421"\w* experience. \w They|strong="H5921"\w* \w each|strong="H3605"\w* carry \w a|strong="H3068"\w* \w sword|strong="H2719"\w* strapped \w to|strong="H5921"\w* \w the|strong="H3605"\w* \w thigh|strong="H3409"\w*, ready \w for|strong="H5921"\w* \w any|strong="H3605"\w* night-time attacks.
\v 9 (\w Solomon|strong="H8010"\w*'s sedan \w chair|strong="H6086"\w*\f + \fr 3:9 \ft “Sedan chair”: a different word is used but the meaning is the same.\f* \w was|strong="H4428"\w* \w made|strong="H6213"\w* \w for|strong="H6213"\w* \w him|strong="H6213"\w* \w with|strong="H6213"\w* \w wood|strong="H6086"\w* \w from|strong="H6086"\w* \w Lebanon|strong="H3844"\w*.
\v 10 \w Its|strong="H6213"\w* \w posts|strong="H5982"\w* \w were|strong="H1323"\w* \w covered|strong="H1323"\w* \w in|strong="H6213"\w* \w silver|strong="H3701"\w*, \w and|strong="H3701"\w* \w the|strong="H6213"\w* \w back|strong="H7507"\w* \w was|strong="H3389"\w* \w covered|strong="H1323"\w* \w in|strong="H6213"\w* \w gold|strong="H2091"\w*. \w The|strong="H6213"\w* \w seat|strong="H4817"\w* cushion \w was|strong="H3389"\w* purple. \w The|strong="H6213"\w* \w interior|strong="H8432"\w* \w was|strong="H3389"\w* lovingly decorated.\f + \fr 3:10 \ft The meaning of the last part of this verse is unclear. Possibly “The interior was inlaid with ivory.”\f*)
\p \w Women|strong="H1323"\w* \w of|strong="H1323"\w* \w Jerusalem|strong="H3389"\w*,
\v 11 \w come|strong="H3318"\w* \w out|strong="H3318"\w*! \w Look|strong="H7200"\w*, \w women|strong="H1323"\w* \w of|strong="H4428"\w* \w Zion|strong="H6726"\w*! \w See|strong="H7200"\w* \w King|strong="H4428"\w* \w Solomon|strong="H8010"\w* wearing \w the|strong="H7200"\w* \w crown|strong="H5850"\w* \w that|strong="H7200"\w* \w his|strong="H7200"\w* mother placed \w on|strong="H3117"\w* \w his|strong="H7200"\w* head \w on|strong="H3117"\w* \w his|strong="H7200"\w* \w wedding|strong="H2861"\w* \w day|strong="H3117"\w*, \w his|strong="H7200"\w* happiest \w day|strong="H3117"\w*.
\b
\c 4
\sp Man:
\p 
\v 1 How \w beautiful|strong="H3303"\w* \w you|strong="H5869"\w* \w look|strong="H2005"\w*, \w my|strong="H1157"\w* \w darling|strong="H7474"\w*, how \w beautiful|strong="H3303"\w*! \w Your|strong="H1157"\w* \w eyes|strong="H5869"\w* \w are|strong="H5869"\w* \w like|strong="H2022"\w* \w doves|strong="H3123"\w* \w behind|strong="H1157"\w* \w your|strong="H1157"\w* \w veil|strong="H6777"\w*. \w Your|strong="H1157"\w* \w hair|strong="H8181"\w* flows down \w like|strong="H2022"\w* \w a|strong="H3068"\w* \w flock|strong="H5739"\w* \w of|strong="H2022"\w* \w goats|strong="H5795"\w*\f + \fr 4:1 \ft Goats were usually black in color so presumably corresponding to the woman's hair.\f* \w descending|strong="H1570"\w* \w Mount|strong="H2022"\w* \w Gilead|strong="H1568"\w*.
\v 2 \w Your|strong="H3605"\w* \w teeth|strong="H8127"\w* \w are|strong="H8127"\w* \w as|strong="H5927"\w* white \w as|strong="H5927"\w* \w a|strong="H3068"\w* \w flock|strong="H5739"\w* \w of|strong="H4480"\w* \w sheep|strong="H4480"\w* \w that|strong="H3605"\w* \w are|strong="H8127"\w* \w just|strong="H3605"\w* \w shorn|strong="H7094"\w* \w and|strong="H5927"\w* washed. \w None|strong="H3605"\w* \w of|strong="H4480"\w* \w them|strong="H5927"\w* \w are|strong="H8127"\w* missing—\w they|strong="H3605"\w* \w are|strong="H8127"\w* \w all|strong="H3605"\w* perfectly matched.\f + \fr 4:2 \ft In other words, each upper tooth is matched by a lower tooth.\f*
\v 3 \w Your|strong="H1157"\w* \w lips|strong="H8193"\w* \w are|strong="H8193"\w* \w as|strong="H5000"\w* \w red|strong="H8144"\w* \w as|strong="H5000"\w* \w scarlet|strong="H8144"\w* \w thread|strong="H2339"\w*. \w Your|strong="H1157"\w* \w mouth|strong="H4057"\w* \w is|strong="H8193"\w* gorgeous. \w Your|strong="H1157"\w* cheeks\f + \fr 4:3 \ft Or “temples.” One of the Dead Sea Scrolls (4Q Canta) can be read as “chin.”\f* \w are|strong="H8193"\w* \w the|strong="H1157"\w* blushing color \w of|strong="H4057"\w* \w pomegranates|strong="H7416"\w* \w behind|strong="H1157"\w* \w your|strong="H1157"\w* \w veil|strong="H6777"\w*.
\v 4 \w Your|strong="H3605"\w* \w neck|strong="H6677"\w* \w is|strong="H3605"\w* \w as|strong="H3605"\w* tall \w and|strong="H1732"\w* shapely \w as|strong="H3605"\w* \w David|strong="H1732"\w*'s \w tower|strong="H4026"\w*, \w with|strong="H5921"\w* \w your|strong="H3605"\w* necklaces \w like|strong="H4043"\w* \w the|strong="H3605"\w* \w hanging|strong="H8518"\w* \w shields|strong="H4043"\w* \w of|strong="H1368"\w* \w a|strong="H3068"\w* thousand \w warriors|strong="H1368"\w*.
\v 5 \w Your|strong="H7462"\w* \w breasts|strong="H7699"\w* \w are|strong="H8147"\w* \w like|strong="H7699"\w* \w two|strong="H8147"\w* \w fawns|strong="H6082"\w*, \w two|strong="H8147"\w* gazelles \w feeding|strong="H7462"\w* \w among|strong="H7799"\w* \w the|strong="H7462"\w* \w lilies|strong="H7799"\w*.
\p 
\v 6 \w Before|strong="H5704"\w* \w the|strong="H3117"\w* morning breezes \w blow|strong="H6315"\w* \w and|strong="H3117"\w* \w the|strong="H3117"\w* \w shadows|strong="H6752"\w* disappear, \w I|strong="H3117"\w* must hurry \w to|strong="H5704"\w* those \w mountains|strong="H2022"\w* \w of|strong="H3117"\w* \w myrrh|strong="H4753"\w*\f + \fr 4:6 \ft See \xt 1:13\xt*\ft .\f* \w and|strong="H3117"\w* \w frankincense|strong="H3828"\w*.
\v 7 \w You|strong="H3605"\w* are incredibly \w beautiful|strong="H3303"\w*, \w my|strong="H3605"\w* \w darling|strong="H7474"\w*—\w you|strong="H3605"\w* are absolutely flawless!
\p 
\v 8 Come \w with|strong="H7218"\w* \w me|strong="H7789"\w* \w from|strong="H7218"\w* \w Lebanon|strong="H3844"\w*, \w my|strong="H7789"\w* \w bride|strong="H3618"\w*, come \w from|strong="H7218"\w* \w Lebanon|strong="H3844"\w*.\f + \fr 4:8 \ft It is thought that Lebanon is used symbolically here (together with the other locations mentioned) as remote and inaccessible.\f* Come \w down|strong="H7218"\w* \w from|strong="H7218"\w* \w the|strong="H7218"\w* peak \w of|strong="H7218"\w* Amana, \w from|strong="H7218"\w* \w the|strong="H7218"\w* peaks \w of|strong="H7218"\w* \w Senir|strong="H8149"\w* \w and|strong="H7218"\w* \w Hermon|strong="H2768"\w*, \w from|strong="H7218"\w* \w the|strong="H7218"\w* lions' \w dens|strong="H4585"\w*, \w from|strong="H7218"\w* \w the|strong="H7218"\w* \w mountains|strong="H2042"\w* where \w leopards|strong="H5246"\w* live.
\v 9 \w You|strong="H5869"\w* \w have|strong="H5869"\w* stolen my \w heart|strong="H3823"\w*, my sister,\f + \fr 4:9 \ft “My sister”: this is a term of endearment and not to be taken literally. Some commentators believe this also applies to the term “bride” which is only used in this section of the book.\f* my \w bride|strong="H3618"\w*. \w With|strong="H5869"\w* just one \w look|strong="H5869"\w* \w you|strong="H5869"\w* stole my \w heart|strong="H3823"\w*, \w with|strong="H5869"\w* just one sparkle \w from|strong="H5869"\w* \w a|strong="H3068"\w* single one \w of|strong="H5869"\w* \w your|strong="H5869"\w* necklaces.
\v 10 \w How|strong="H4100"\w* wonderful \w is|strong="H4100"\w* \w your|strong="H3605"\w* \w love|strong="H1730"\w*, \w my|strong="H3605"\w* sister, \w my|strong="H3605"\w* \w bride|strong="H3618"\w*! \w Your|strong="H3605"\w* \w love|strong="H1730"\w* \w is|strong="H4100"\w* sweeter \w than|strong="H3605"\w* \w wine|strong="H3196"\w*. \w The|strong="H3605"\w* \w way|strong="H3605"\w* \w you|strong="H3605"\w* \w smell|strong="H7381"\w* \w from|strong="H3196"\w* \w your|strong="H3605"\w* perfumed \w oils|strong="H8081"\w* \w is|strong="H4100"\w* \w better|strong="H2895"\w* \w than|strong="H3605"\w* \w any|strong="H3605"\w* \w spice|strong="H1314"\w*.
\v 11 Nectar drips \w from|strong="H8478"\w* \w your|strong="H8478"\w* \w lips|strong="H8193"\w*; \w milk|strong="H2461"\w* \w and|strong="H2461"\w* \w honey|strong="H1706"\w* \w are|strong="H8193"\w* \w under|strong="H8478"\w* \w your|strong="H8478"\w* \w tongue|strong="H3956"\w*. \w The|strong="H8478"\w* \w smell|strong="H7381"\w* \w of|strong="H8478"\w* \w your|strong="H8478"\w* \w clothes|strong="H8008"\w* \w is|strong="H3956"\w* \w like|strong="H8478"\w* \w the|strong="H8478"\w* \w fragrance|strong="H7381"\w* \w of|strong="H8478"\w* \w Lebanon|strong="H3844"\w*.
\p 
\v 12 My sister, my \w bride|strong="H3618"\w*, is \w a|strong="H3068"\w* \w locked|strong="H5274"\w* \w garden|strong="H1588"\w*, \w a|strong="H3068"\w* \w spring|strong="H4599"\w* \w of|strong="H1588"\w* water that is closed, \w a|strong="H3068"\w* \w fountain|strong="H4599"\w* that is \w sealed|strong="H2856"\w*.
\v 13 \w Your|strong="H5973"\w* channel\f + \fr 4:13 \ft Continuing the metaphor of a spring and fountain.\f* \w is|strong="H6529"\w* \w a|strong="H3068"\w* paradise \w of|strong="H6529"\w* \w pomegranates|strong="H7416"\w*, full \w of|strong="H6529"\w* \w the|strong="H5973"\w* best \w fruits|strong="H6529"\w*, \w with|strong="H5973"\w* \w henna|strong="H3724"\w* \w and|strong="H5973"\w* \w nard|strong="H5373"\w*,\f + \fr 4:13 \ft “Henna and nard”: two exotic perfumes.\f*
\v 14 \w nard|strong="H5373"\w* \w and|strong="H6086"\w* \w saffron|strong="H3750"\w*, \w calamus|strong="H7070"\w* \w and|strong="H6086"\w* \w cinnamon|strong="H7076"\w*, \w with|strong="H5973"\w* \w all|strong="H3605"\w* \w kinds|strong="H3605"\w* \w of|strong="H7218"\w* \w trees|strong="H6086"\w* producing \w frankincense|strong="H3828"\w*, \w myrrh|strong="H4753"\w*, aloes, \w and|strong="H6086"\w* \w the|strong="H3605"\w* \w finest|strong="H7218"\w* \w spices|strong="H1314"\w*.
\v 15 \w You|strong="H4480"\w* \w are|strong="H4325"\w* \w a|strong="H3068"\w* \w garden|strong="H1588"\w* \w fountain|strong="H4599"\w*, \w a|strong="H3068"\w* \w well|strong="H4599"\w* \w of|strong="H4325"\w* \w living|strong="H2416"\w* \w water|strong="H4325"\w*, \w a|strong="H3068"\w* \w flowing|strong="H5140"\w* \w stream|strong="H4325"\w* \w from|strong="H4480"\w* \w Lebanon|strong="H3844"\w*.\f + \fr 4:15 \ft Some commentators believe that in contrast to the images of verse 12 that speak of a sealed fountain that what was once locked is now open. Others believe that this is now the words of the woman and should begin with “I am…” (No verb is supplied in the Hebrew.)\f*
\sp Woman:
\p 
\v 16 \w Wake|strong="H5782"\w* \w up|strong="H5782"\w*, \w north|strong="H6828"\w* \w wind|strong="H8486"\w*! Come, \w south|strong="H8486"\w* \w wind|strong="H8486"\w*! \w Blow|strong="H6315"\w* on \w my|strong="H5782"\w* \w garden|strong="H1588"\w* \w so|strong="H5782"\w* \w its|strong="H6529"\w* scent may be carried on \w the|strong="H5782"\w* breeze. Let \w my|strong="H5782"\w* \w love|strong="H1730"\w* come \w to|strong="H6828"\w* \w his|strong="H5782"\w* \w garden|strong="H1588"\w* \w and|strong="H6828"\w* eat \w its|strong="H6529"\w* best \w fruits|strong="H6529"\w*.
\b
\c 5
\sp Man:
\p 
\v 1 I enter \w my|strong="H8354"\w* \w garden|strong="H1588"\w*, \w my|strong="H8354"\w* sister, \w my|strong="H8354"\w* \w bride|strong="H3618"\w*! I gather \w myrrh|strong="H4753"\w* \w with|strong="H5973"\w* \w my|strong="H8354"\w* \w spice|strong="H1313"\w*. I eat \w my|strong="H8354"\w* \w honeycomb|strong="H1706"\w* \w with|strong="H5973"\w* \w my|strong="H8354"\w* \w honey|strong="H1706"\w*. I \w drink|strong="H8354"\w* \w wine|strong="H3196"\w* \w with|strong="H5973"\w* \w my|strong="H8354"\w* \w milk|strong="H2461"\w*. Let us eat \w our|strong="H5973"\w* fill \w of|strong="H1588"\w* \w love|strong="H1730"\w*! Let us be \w drunk|strong="H8354"\w* \w with|strong="H5973"\w* \w love|strong="H1730"\w*!\f + \fr 5:1 \ft Some take this last line as being spoken by the women of Jerusalem, in which case it could be translated, “Friends, eat and drink, and become drunk with love.”\f*
\sp Woman:
\p 
\v 2 Though \w I|strong="H3820"\w* \w was|strong="H3820"\w* \w asleep|strong="H3462"\w*, \w my|strong="H6605"\w* \w mind|strong="H3820"\w*\f + \fr 5:2 \ft “Mind”: literally, “heart,” but in Hebrew the heart is primarily the source of thought. Emotions are more often located in the bowels. (See e.g. KJV for \xt Genesis 43:30\xt*\ft ; \xt Lamentations 1:20\xt*\ft etc. and even in this very chapter—verse 4, translated here as “deep inside.”)\f* \w was|strong="H3820"\w* racing. \w I|strong="H3820"\w* \w heard|strong="H6963"\w* \w my|strong="H6605"\w* \w love|strong="H1730"\w* \w knocking|strong="H1849"\w*, \w and|strong="H6963"\w* calling \w out|strong="H6605"\w*, “Please \w open|strong="H6605"\w* \w the|strong="H4390"\w* door, \w my|strong="H6605"\w* sister, \w my|strong="H6605"\w* \w darling|strong="H7474"\w*, \w my|strong="H6605"\w* \w dove|strong="H3123"\w*, \w my|strong="H6605"\w* \w perfect|strong="H8535"\w* \w love|strong="H1730"\w*. \w My|strong="H6605"\w* \w head|strong="H7218"\w* \w is|strong="H3820"\w* soaked \w with|strong="H4390"\w* \w dew|strong="H2919"\w*, \w my|strong="H6605"\w* \w hair|strong="H7218"\w* \w is|strong="H3820"\w* wet \w from|strong="H3820"\w* \w the|strong="H4390"\w* \w night|strong="H3915"\w* mist.”
\p 
\v 3 I replied,\f + \fr 5:3 \ft Implied.\f* “I've already got undressed. I don't \w have|strong="H7272"\w* \w to|strong="H7272"\w* get \w dressed|strong="H3847"\w* again, do I? I've already \w washed|strong="H7364"\w* \w my|strong="H7364"\w* \w feet|strong="H7272"\w*. I don't \w have|strong="H7272"\w* \w to|strong="H7272"\w* \w make|strong="H7272"\w* \w them|strong="H3847"\w* \w dirty|strong="H2936"\w* again, do I?”
